924 massacre of Filipino sugar workers in Hawai'i pairs with statistical relentlessness of Black economic suffering to shed light on hidden dimensions of mass ignorance and indifference. The histories of Asians, Blacks, Latina/os, and Natives relate in knotty ways. State violence and colonialism come to the fore in taking measure of the United States, past and present, while the undue importance of assimilation and colorblindness recedes. Ultimately, Jung challenges the dominant racial common sense and develops new concepts and theory for radically rethinking and resisting racisms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aMinoritiesxSocial conditionsxUnited States. 0aMinoritieszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aRacismxUnited States. 0aRacismzUnited States. 4aAssimilation. 4aEmpire-State. 4aJames Baldwin. 4aNation-State. 4aPolitics of National Belonging. 4aRacial State. 4aRacism. 4aSymbolic Coercion. 4aSymbolic Perversity. 4aSymbolic Violence. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479522740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804795227423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804795227.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles